SIMPLE: grub
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Grub
<hw>Grub</hw> <pr>(gr⟦ucr⟧b)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Grubbed</conjf> <pr>(gr⟦ucr⟧bd)</pr>, <pos>p. pr. &
vb. n.</pos> <conjf>Grubbing</conjf> <pr>(<?/)</pr>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE.
<ets>grubbin</ets>., cf. E. <ets>grab</ets>, <ets>grope</ets>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To dig in or under the ground, generally for an object
that is difficult to reach or extricate; to be occupied in
digging.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To drudge; to do menial work.</def>
<rj><au>Richardson.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grub</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Grub
<hw>Grub</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To dig; to dig up by
the roots; to root out by digging; -- followed by up; <as>as, to
<ex>grub</ex> up trees, rushes, or sedge</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They do not attempt to <qex>grub</qex> up the root of sin.</q>
<rj><qau>Hare.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To supply with food.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>
<rj><au>Dickens.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Grub</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Grub
<hw>Grub</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <def>The
larva of an insect, especially of a beetle; -- called also
<altname>grubworm</altname>. See <it>Illust.</it> of <cref>Goldsmith
beetle</cref>, under <er>Goldsmith</er>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Yet your butterfly was a <qex>grub</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A short, thick man; a dwarf.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Carew.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Victuals; food.</def> <mark>[Slang]</mark>
<rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<cs><p><mcol><col><b>Grub ax</b></col> <it>or</it> <col><b>Grub
axe</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a kind of mattock used in grubbing up roots,
etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Grub breaker</b></col>. <cd>Same as <er>Grub
hook</er> (<xex>below</xex>).</cd> -- <col><b>Grub hoe</b></col>, <cd>a
heavy hoe for grubbing.</cd> -- <col><b>Grub hook</b></col>, <cd>a
plowlike implement for uprooting stumps, breaking roots, etc.</cd> --
<col><b>Grub saw</b></col>, <cd>a handsaw used for sawing marble.</cd>
-- <col><b>Grub Street</b></col>, <cd>a street in London (now called
<altname>Milton Street</altname>), described by Dr. Johnson as
⟦ldquo⟧much inhabited by writers of small histories, dictionaries, and
temporary poems, whence any mean production is called
<xex>grubstreet</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ As an adjective, suitable to, or
resembling the production of, Grub Street.</cd>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>I 'd sooner ballads write, and <qex>grubstreet</qex> lays.</q>
<rj><qau>Gap.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p></cs>

<p><ent>Grubber</ent>⟦br⟧
